 free-spirited daughter Gitta. She is haunted by memories of a daughter who died in childhood and anxious about a risky, late pregnancy. With her domestic harmony threatened by her own stirrings of autonomy and her children's growing independence, Anneliese finds the future both frightening and promising. The edition is fully annotated, with a critical introduction and bibliography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInterpersonal conflictvFiction. 0aMarried peoplevFiction. 0aParent and adult childvFiction. 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aTwentieth century German literature.1 aBeck, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhitinger, Raleigh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800102378?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800102378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800102378/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles